sec.p:
Burt expressed his dualist views on a number of occasions, e.g. ‘normal psychology reveals within itself an inescapable dualism’ (Burt, 1961a: 86); ‘there must be a ghost in the machine’;
49
 ‘I believe that many, if not all, the processes of consciousness which are at present regarded as normal, will, in many of their aspects, turn out to be quite as independent of the physiological processes of the brain as those which at present are classed as paranormal’ (Burt, 1961b: 30). He considered mechanism outmoded, invoking quantum theory: ‘it would seem there is nothing whatever in contemporary physics which would preclude the apparent anomalies presented by psi phenomena’ (ibid.: 29). Brown (1929: 17) likewise drew attention to the significance of Bohr’s discovery that electrons could move from one orbit to another, without apparently traversing the intermediate space, though he considered reliance on quantum theory to support parapsychological phenomena was premature (Brown, 1932−3: 75).
